{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521519"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:35:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:35:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13689"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13689"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.08,0.07,0.08,0.68]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6297"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52928"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6297","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6297"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13689"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38323"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2262"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11771"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43431"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52928"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a six-month history of chronic cough. He does not have any other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has a 10 pack-year smoking history. On examination, he appears well with his pulse rate of 73/min, blood pressure 126/77 mmHg, respiratory rate 13/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Cardiorespiratory examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA chest X-ray is performed, which reveals a 2 cm well-circumscribed nodule in the right middle lobe. A contrast-enhanced CT chest confirms a solitary, well-circumscribed nodule in the right middle lobe with no evidence of contrast enhancement (Images 1-2). Comparison with a chest X-ray from 10 years ago shows the lesion has remained unchanged in size (Image 3).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bronchogenic carcinoma","Pulmonary arteriovenous malformation","Sarcoidosis","Tuberculosis","Pulmonary hamartoma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe key features of this case are the incidental finding on chest imaging of a solitary, well-circumscribed lung nodule that has remained stable in size over a 10-year period. The contrast-enhanced CT showed no evidence of enhancement within the lesion. These findings are most consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003Epulmonary hamartoma\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the most common benign lung tumour and are common incidental findings on chest X-ray or CT. Importantly, pulmonary hamartomas are very slow-growing and usually remain stable in size over many years, as seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese tumours can be composed of cartilage, fat, fibrous tissue, and smooth muscle. They most commonly occur in the peripheral lung fields and are more frequent in the upper lobes. Pulmonary hamartomas have a peak incidence in the fifth and sixth decades of life, but can occur in younger patients as seen in this 34-year-old man.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchogenic carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E would be expected to grow more rapidly and would be unlikely to remain stable over a 10-year period. The patient\u0027s smoking history raises suspicion for bronchogenic carcinoma, but the long-term stability of the lesion argues against this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epulmonary arteriovenous malformation (AVM)\u003C/strong\u003E may appear as a well-circumscribed nodule on chest imaging. However, a key feature of AVMs is that they enhance with contrast on CT due to their vascular nature. The lack of contrast enhancement in this case makes AVM unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcoidosis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with pulmonary nodules, but these are typically multiple and bilateral. Sarcoidosis nodules also tend to have irregular margins and are often associated with hilar lymphadenopathy. The solitary, well-circumscribed nodule without lymphadenopathy in this case is not typical for sarcoidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETuberculosis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with a solitary pulmonary nodule. However, tuberculous nodules often have irregular margins and are associated with hilar lymphadenopathy. The well-circumscribed appearance and lack of lymphadenopathy in this case make tuberculosis less likely. Additionally, the long-term stability of the lesion over 10 years would be atypical for tuberculosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pulmonary hamartomas the most common benign lung tumour and are often an incidental finding on chest imaging. They are slow-growing and usually remain stable in size over many years.","Pulmonary hamartomas typically appear as a solitary, well-circumscribed nodule on chest X-ray or CT.","Pulmonary hamartomas most commonly occur in the peripheral lung fields and are more frequent in the upper lobes."],"references":["Schmid-Bindert G, Vogel-Claussen J, Gutz S, et al. Incidental Pulmonary Nodules What Do We Know in 2022. Respiration. 2022;101:1024\u201334. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9945197/","Lundeen KS, Raj MS, Rajasurya V, et al. Pulmonary Hamartoma. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539806/#"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38323"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13689"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20646"},{"type":"media","id":"20647"},{"type":"media","id":"20648"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20646"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5k4MkVGvQmrV5DT9fXY3R6JSAhPijL.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5k4MkVGvQmrV5DT9fXY3R6JSAhPijL.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":452,"height":420}},{"type":"media","id":"20647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20647"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/zYRyFjH4PxiiO668dirB3a8paYATwq.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/zYRyFjH4PxiiO668dirB3a8paYATwq.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":461,"height":376}},{"type":"media","id":"20648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20648"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fC4M1uRlqrF94INinZOxPPYmE6mjMJ.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fC4M1uRlqrF94INinZOxPPYmE6mjMJ.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":542,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38323"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-13T08:29:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-13T08:30:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6297"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52928"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships"